The paper deals with a distributed consensus problem, which is a fundamental problem in distributed computing. The focus is on the communication cost of achieving consensus, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category. The use of finite automata and Poisson clocks suggests that the paper may also be relevant to Information Theory (cs.IT) and Systems and Control (cs.SY). The application of the model to blockchains and sensor networks suggests that the paper may also be relevant to Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI).
